Actually I did buy a copy.  Clearly I think very highly of Jefimenko's
work (awestruck is a better expression)  as I based mine on it.
Though it is a very fine book, it appeared to me to be mainly a
consolidation of Jefimenko's life work.  I only browsed it
superficiallly though, for that reason.  I apologize for this late
response to your remark, as I wanted to look it over again to see if I
missed something.  As noted various places in my article, Jefimanko's
work is the foundation upon which I have built.  My addition is the
incremental step of building a full isomorphism by making the mass
charge and field units imaginary.  (Note that Jefimenko's bold face i
is a unit vector, not  the imaginary i = (-1)^(1/2) used in my units.
I have posted articles in this regard since 2003.  Some of my early
thinking is loacted at:

http://www.mtaonline.net/~hheffner/GR-and-QM.pdf
http://www.mtaonline.net/~hheffner/Gravimagnetism.pdf

I did find some material I overlooked.  Most interesting is Chapter
17, especially 17-1.11.  I'll have to think about that a bit.  It
provides some basis for EM and GK field coupling, which is great,
though I am not still sure I understand the initial assumptions
leading there.  The bending of light section that follows is very
interesting, though it doesn't deal with negative gravitational
objects, which was my focus.

Also notable is the reference to negative gravitational fields on page
311, and formula 19-1.6, which is roughly similar to the formula I
derived for the glactic mass distribuiton to solve the galactic
rotation problem.  Jefimenko's basis for that formula was including
the effects of the mass equivalent of the energy of the gravitional
field. Though that sounds rational, I personally can not buy the
notion that gravitons,or gravitational fields, self-interact, because
black holes would then be impossible.  I still think neagtive
gravitaional charge is the likely source, and the existence of such
chrage is mandated by the fundamental assumption that the isomorphism
exists, which is not a long stretch of logic. Further, such charge
represents and exaplains the &quot;negative energy&quot; problem and a variety
of others, and fleshes out the entire realm of gravimagnetic
formulations, not just those Jefimeko lists. Jefimenko is still in the
unfortunate position of having to determine equation signs on a case
by case basis.

