One of the things that I have learned in reading Jefimenko is that I have to
be VERY careful. Most writers, upon deriving a new concept, will usually
highlight the finding with stars, circles, lines and -- if they can manage
it -- music and dancing girls. In contrast, Jefimenko is wont to allow a new
concept to slide in with no fanfare whatsoever.

As an example, I completley missed, on first reading, the significance of
INDUCTION as being a non-magnetic phenomenon! Phooosh! It went right by me.
At 3:00 AM I awoke with an &quot;omigosh!&quot;

So, Caveat Lector. I'm re-reading (more carefully) the Gravitation book.
Already found a couple of little &quot;zingers.&quot; Kinda like -- at Easter time --
going BACK into the yard to find the eggs that I missed the first time out
with my basket!

